		<title>Doctor Who 50th Anniversary&#8230;</title>
		<link>https://www.g400.co.uk/cantabits/archives/1863</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Mark]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sat, 26 Oct 2013 23:00:50 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Film]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Music]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.g400.co.uk/cantabits/archives/1863</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[It&#8217;s impressive when a television programme reaches a large milestone &#8211; particularly a fictional television programme (chat shows are a bit easier to keep going, and the news and weather don&#8217;t count). Coming to cinemas worldwide and television screens in &#8230; <a href="https://www.g400.co.uk/cantabits/archives/1863">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>It&#8217;s impressive when a television programme reaches a large milestone &#8211; particularly a fictional television programme (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Late_Late_Show">chat shows</a> are a bit easier to keep going, and the news and weather don&#8217;t count). Coming to cinemas worldwide and television screens in the British Isles next month is an episode of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doctor_Who">Doctor Who</a> to celebrate the show reaching its 50th anniversary. The trailer below, which has a nice but brief take on the iconic theme music, celebrates Doctor Who&#8217;s long history, featuring relics from every era of the show along with an impressive re-animation of characters (and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doctor_(Doctor_Who)">Doctors</a>) past and present. I can only hope that on the 23rd of November, the 50th anniversary episode does the show equal justice.</p>
